<concept id="c_performing_arts">
    <title>Performing arts</title>
    <shortdesc/>
    <conbody>
        <p>The city has several famous theatres, including the Narodowy Stary Teatr (the <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Old_Theatre" format="html"
                scope="external">National Old Theatre</xref>),<sup><xref
                    href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krak%C3%B3w#cite_note-Stary_Teatr_w_Krakowie,_homepage_in_Polish-201"
                    format="html" scope="external">[200]</xref></sup> the <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Juliusz_S%C5%82owacki_Theatre" format="html"
                scope="external">Juliusz Słowacki Theatre</xref>, the Bagatela Theatre, the <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ludowy_Theatre" format="html" scope="external"
                >Ludowy Theatre</xref>, and the Groteska Theatre of Puppetry, as well as the <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Opera_Krakowska" format="html" scope="external"
                >Opera Krakowska</xref> and Kraków Operetta. The city's principal concert hall and
            the home of the <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krak%C3%B3w_Philharmonic_Orchestra"
                format="html" scope="external">Kraków Philharmonic Orchestra</xref> is the <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krak%C3%B3w_Philharmonic" format="html"
                scope="external">Kraków Philharmonic</xref> (<i>Filharmonia Krakowska</i>) built in
                    1931.<sup><xref
                    href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krak%C3%B3w#cite_note-KP-202" format="html"
                    scope="external">[201]</xref></sup></p>
        <p>Kraków hosts many annual and biannual artistic events,<sup><xref
                    href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krak%C3%B3w#cite_note-krakow.pl-1-203"
                    format="html" scope="external">[202]</xref></sup> some of international
            significance such as the Misteria Paschalia (Baroque music), Sacrum-Profanum
            (contemporary music), the Krakow Screen Festival (<xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Popular_music" format="html" scope="external"
                >popular music</xref>), the Festival of <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Music_of_Poland" format="html" scope="external"
                >Polish Music</xref> (classical music), Dedications (theatre), the <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krak%C3%B3w_Film_Festival" format="html"
                scope="external">Kraków Film Festival</xref> (one of Europe's oldest short films
                    events),<sup><xref
                    href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krak%C3%B3w#cite_note-Krakowski_Festiwal_Filmowy-204"
                    format="html" scope="external">[203]</xref></sup>
            <xref href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Etiuda%26Anima_International_Film_Festival"
                format="html" scope="external">Etiuda&amp;Anima International Film Festival</xref>
            (the oldest international art-film event in Poland), Biennial of <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graphic_arts" format="html" scope="external"
                >Graphic Arts</xref>, and the <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jewish_Culture_Festival" format="html"
                scope="external">Jewish Culture Festival</xref>. Kraków was the residence of two
            Polish <xref href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nobel_Prize" format="html"
                scope="external">Nobel</xref> laureates in literature, <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wis%C5%82awa_Szymborska" format="html"
                scope="external">Wisława Szymborska</xref> and <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Czes%C5%82aw_Mi%C5%82osz" format="html"
                scope="external">Czesław Miłosz</xref>; a third <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Nobel_laureates" format="html"
                scope="external">Nobel laureate</xref>, the Yugoslav writer <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ivo_Andri%C4%87" format="html" scope="external"
                >Ivo Andric</xref>, lived and studied in Kraków. Other former longtime residents
            include internationally renowned <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cinema_of_Poland" format="html" scope="external"
                >Polish film</xref> directors <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrzej_Wajda" format="html" scope="external"
                >Andrzej Wajda</xref> and <xref href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roman_Polanski"
                format="html" scope="external">Roman Polanski</xref>, both of whom are <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Academy_Award" format="html" scope="external"
                >Academy Award</xref> winners.</p>
    </conbody>
